        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>LEAD: To the Editor:</p>
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If our stance in the Middle East is indeed ''striking a blow for the principle that might does not make right,'' as President Bush told Pentagon employees (news article, Aug. 16), why is he using might, in the form of Stealth bombers and thousands of troops, to prove that we are right? Surely, if the behavior of a neighbor threatens ''our way of life,'' there are other ways we can deal with that threat, such as changing our way of life, rather than preparing to sacrifice thousands of American and Iraqi lives for a commodity.</p>
        <p>Personally, I'd rather drive a car powered by alcohol, and heat my home with coal, than lose any of my grandsons.</p>
        <p>RENA G. KUNIS</p>
        <p>Bellerose, Queens, Aug. 16, 1990</p>
      </block>
